WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCK PRICES PLUNGED in a broad sell-off that began in
European markets. The Dow Jones industrials fell 52.48 points
to 2603.96 in hectic trading. Bonds closed slightly lower
after falling sharply early in the day. The dollar rose
against the yen but fell against the mark.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   European stock prices sank on rumors of Mideast fighting.
Germany's blue-chip DAX Index plunged 5.2%. London's FT-SE
100 retreated 2.3%.
   ---
   Gasoline and oil prices swung wildly, ending mostly
higher. Separately, the Energy Department doesn't expect to
tap the Strategic Petroleum Reserve until next month at the
earliest, barring more fighting.
                                                                                                       

   Salomon is benefiting from soaring oil prices, through the
Wall Street firm's Phibro Energy unit.
   ---
   U.S. car makers shaved more than 53,000 vehicles from
planned third-quarter output, apparently due to uncertainty
related to the Mideast. More reductions could come this week.
   ---
   MCI is speeding up the conversion of its network to
digital technology, which will result in marketing
advantages, lower operating costs and a likely write-down of
old equipment that could total $550 million.
   ---
   National Semiconductor intends to eliminate several
product groups, lay off 2,000, or 6.2%, of its employees, and
incur a $140 million charge.
   ---
   Wang won a federal computer contract valued at up to $841
million over five years. The deal is a big boost for the
firm, which has been struggling with huge losses and
declining sales.
   ---
   Donald Trump won approval from New Jersey casino
authorities for his $65 million bank bailout.
   ---
   Manville asbestos plaintiffs' attorneys fees were capped
at 20% of claims by a federal judge.
   ---
   USAir is firing about 1,500, or 3%, of its workers, and
indicated more cutbacks are likely. Separately, the carrier
lost a bitter union battle.
   ---
   The U.S. budget gap was $25.93 billion in July, over $7
billion more than in July 1989, the government said. Higher
spending was blamed.
   ---
   Short interest for the month ended Aug. 15 rose 4.1% to a
record volume on the Big Board, but fell slightly on the
American Stock Exchange.
   ---
   American International Group's falling stock price may
force the insurer to sweeten its bid for International Lease
Finance in order to salvage the $1.3 billion transaction.
   ---
   Stotler settled charges with commodities regulators, but
the closed futures brokerage firm still faces a hearing
before securities officials.
   ---
   IBM introduced three low-end minicomputers that could
compete with personal computers and workstations.
   ---
   PepsiCo expects to post a $50 million third-quarter gain
from the sale of Kentucky Fried Chicken stock in Japan, which
will more than offset $45 million in charges in the period.
   ---
   NVR Limited Partnership posted a $53.3 million
second-quarter loss, due mainly to a restructuring. The
homebuilder and developer said it will omit a quarterly
payout to unit holders.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 194,630,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
